FARLEY STICKING TO FORMULA


By STEPHEN PHILLIPS, Special to the New York Times


Published: April 26, 1986









CHICAGO, April 25— 
                    William F. Farley, who turned a $25,000 investment into a $2 billion empire in less than 10 years, likes to talk in the jargon of baseball.        

                    Mr. Farley, a 43-year-old part-owner of the Chicago White Sox, rates one of his less successful deals, the Condec Corporation, as a single, and boasts how his $1.4 billion acquisition last year of Northwest Industries has ''home run potential.''        

                    In his eagerness to pile up runs for Farley Industries, the umbrella organization for his holdings, he is willing to make an occasional sacrifice play. Various operations have been sold and inventory adjustments have been made to improve overall performance, even though the moves have produced lower revenues and losses.        

                    For example, Farley/Northwest Industries, the name Mr. Farley gave to Chicago-based Northwest, lost $72.9 million last year, after earning $77.5 million a year earlier. Condec, a maker of electronic controls acquired in 1984, has lost more than $24 million in the last two years while it was also suffering declines in sales.        

                    There are those who see some perils in the Farley situation. ''Things are pretty tight,'' said Steven Brooks, a senior analyst with Moody's Investor Services, which recently downgraded the senior debt ratings on both Farley/Northwest and Condec because of their heavy debt. ''Given how leveraged up he is, he doesn't have a lot of leeway.''        

                    But Mr. Farley argues that the right moves are being made. ''If you're private,'' he said, ''you don't try to maximize reported earnings.''        

                    ''We're hardly under water,'' the trim, tan executive said in the spacious headquarters in the Sears Tower that he and his corporate staff of 25 inherited with the Northwest deal. ''We just paid off millions of dollars of bank debt.''        

                    Also, company officials have indicated that an announcement of a ''major restructuring'' involving Condec will be made soon. Some Moves Are Praised        

                    Most analysts agree with Mr. Farley that his pruning of Northwest, in particular, has been worthwhile. Among the moves he has made are taking a $52.6 million loss on the sale of the Pogo Producing Company, an oil and gas exploration company, and selling for $225 million the agrichemical division of the troubled Velsicol Chemical Corporation. He plans to sell the small remaining portion of Velsicol by the end of the year.        

                    What remains in the Northwest unit are one stellar business - Union Underwear, which markets under the Fruit of the Loom and B.V.D. labels - and two solid, but less impressive, operations - the General Battery Corporation, the nation's second-largest maker of replacement batteries for cars, and Acme Boot, whose products include the Dingo footwear line.        

                    A slimmer Northwest, beefed up by increased spending for such things as advertising, has considerable profit potential, according to Leon D. Black, a managing director at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.        

                    ''The picture had been cloudy because of Velsicol,'' he said, ''but with the asset sales, the numbers have already improved in a short period.'' What remains at Northwest, he said, ''is a future that looks very good.'' Two Leading Brands        

                    With Fruit of the Loom and B.V.D., Union controls 72 percent of the mass-merchandise underwear market. The unit had 1985 sales of $580 million and operating income of about $95 million, generating about 90 percent of the Northwest unit's operating income.        

                    Analysts say Union has a strong history. ''Fruit of the Loom did to men's underwear, what Hanes did to ladies' nylons,'' said W. Dudley Herr, an analyst with Duff & Phelps. ''They marketed underwear away from department stores to just about any retail outlet - grocery stores, five and dimes, you name it.''        

                    And it is here that Mr. Farley has his biggest plans. Hoping to capitalize on its distribution base, Farley will begin to strongly promote women's underwear as well as add men's and women's socks and sweatshirts to Union's product line later this year. According to Mr. Farley's estimates, socks and sweatshirts will add about $50 million in sales in 1986.        

                    Increasing Union's product line will not be easy, cautioned W. Dudley Herr, an analyst at Duff & Phelps. ''Stores just don't give a lot of play to Fruit of the Loom products now,'' he said. ''How he's going to get places like K Mart to clear even more shelf space is anybody's guess.''        

                    If Union is the strongest part of the Farley empire, analysts say Condec is the weak spot. In 1984, he bought the 90 percent of Condec that he did not own for $139 million.        

                    For the year ending in July 1985, the latest figures available, Condec had a loss of $9.75 million, on revenues of $215.5 million. In 1984 it lost $14.65 million. Mr. Farley said Condec was not very healthy when he purchased it - an assertion that is disputed by some former Condec officials. A Pentagon Investigation        

                    The Condec troubles have not been limited to finances. Condiesel, a unit, has been the target of a $20 million Department of Defense overcharge investigation. To make matters worse, its largest contract, carriage assemblies for howitzer armored vehicles, expired this month.        







